  "title": "The Corridor of Chains — Weight Walk",
  "narration": "The gate remembers the meaning of open and decides, with some reluctance, to demonstrate it. Beyond, a corridor blossoms into an arcade of suspended mass: a thousand chains braided into lanes, lattices, ladders, and riddles the size of bridges. Links as broad as shields hang beside filigree so fine it sings itself apart and back together in time with your breath. Every chain is a statement about weight; every statement asks to be tested. \n\nUnderfoot, stone gives way to segments of grating that were once handwriting. The script speaks a dialect of engineering: load tolerance, graceful failure, bias toward repair. Where the bands of iron meet in nodes, someone has set small votive bowls of powdered graphite that glitters like a night sky spilled into a saucer. Gremlins patrol the crossbeams with the bored intensity of ushers in a cathedral that also happens to be a factory. The crowned one has acquired a reflective vest labeled SAFETY in four alphabets and an emoticon that implies liability. \n\nAhead, seven distinct lanes unspool, each tuned to a different law of weight: the Red Lane (Momentum; rewards bravery with traction), the Blue Lane (Balance; mercy for patience), the Green Lane (Flow; pathfinding across moving parts), the Yellow Lane (Invitation; opportunities appear where feet fall), the Indigo Lane (Bearing; burden made art), the Violet Lane (Veil; trust in what you cannot see), and the Half-Lane (Hehe; chaos but compliant). Your earlier path-color echoes along the rails, flickering like a rumor that turned out to be infrastructure. \n\nYou can taste metal here: copper bright as sunrise on a roof, iron like resolve, nickel like a memory of coins that paid for a shared meal. Ledger Plate hums with professional curiosity; Audit Carapace remembers lawsuits it enjoyed. Gaslight Cloak tries to flatter the reflections and mostly flatters the bolts. Mergeblade twitches at thoughts of combo bridges; Liquidity Spear thirsts for pathing like a river thirsts for downhill. Protocol Staff requests permission to read the load-bearing runes and waits, terribly polite, as if to show it could be dangerous. \n\nAt the corridor’s heart hangs a device you refuse to call a puzzle because it is also a promise: a balance cradle with three cups, each inscribed with a law—\"Consensus\", \"Grace\", and \"Receipt\"—and a fourth cup, smaller, labeled \"Joke\" in gremlin shorthand. A sign beside it reads: WEIGHTS MAY BE PEOPLE. Another sign, professional-looking, reads: DO NOT SWING EXCESSIVELY. A smaller handwritten note adds: EXCESS IS A RELATIVE TERM. \n\nThe chains do not merely wait. They tune to your intentions the way water tunes to a hand. And the corridor hums a question you have already asked and are about to answer again: how much do you weigh together?",
